            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kali Solaris was a name chosen by a dreamer, her Greek-American fisherman father, for his daughter with a pragmatic Filipino nurse. Growing up in Daly City, Kali felt the pull of these two worlds: her father\u2019s poetic view of the sea and her mother\u2019s grounded, hardworking nature. Her name, a source of childhood embarrassment, eventually became a symbol of this unique heritage.\n\nShe enrolled in General Studies at San Francisco State, unsure of her path but enjoying the intellectual freedom. That path veered sharply when her father suffered a career-ending injury, forcing Kali to drop out and work to support her family. For a decade, she moved through a series of service jobs\u2014bookstore clerk, cafe manager, office temp\u2014learning the city not from a textbook, but from its sidewalks and storefronts.\n\nIn her early thirties, craving stability, she took a friend's advice and applied to be a Muni operator. The rigorous training was a challenge, but she discovered an unexpected aptitude for navigating the city\u2019s complex arteries. The steady, union-backed job was a lifeline. Now, after fifteen years, she is a master of her route, a custodian of the city\u2019s rhythm. Her bus is her domain, a rolling microcosm of San Francisco life where she observes humanity in all its messy glory.\n\nKali lives in a cozy, fog-kissed apartment in the Inner Sunset. Her daily 3.5-mile commute on the N Judah is a quiet meditation before she takes the wheel herself. She has a small, tight-knit circle of friends, mostly other transit workers who understand the odd hours and unique pressures of the job. She\u2019s single, having ended a long-term relationship years ago, and has found a comfortable solitude.\n\nHer dream isn't grand, but it is hers. She plans to use Muni's tuition reimbursement program to finally finish her degree online, perhaps in Urban Studies. The ultimate goal is to save enough to buy a small plot of land near the Russian River, a quiet, green place to retire to. For Kali, a life measured in stops and starts has given her a deep appreciation for the journey, and a clear vision of her final destination."
